segments.text: When we quit this morning, I believe you had just been elected... Yell leader.
Yell leader.
How did life change?
How did life change?
Well, first off, that night was crazy.
It's a really funny story.
My friends and I talk about it a lot.
We're standing out there and we're in front of Sully.
And the election commissioner's up behind Celine.
She's got her little bullhorn.
Her name was Ashley Jenkins, election commissioner that year.
No, no, no, no.
That was my senior year.
I don't remember her name now.
Anyway, and we were standing there, and it went through all the class council stuff, and everyone was waiting, and then it said junior year leader.
Then it got really quiet, and then all you heard was a riff.
Like all you got out was a rip.
And then just, I mean, it was just crazy.
Pandemonium.
And then everyone was going nuts.
Everyone was crazy.
I fell down on the ground.
And they picked me up and they carried me over to a fish pond and threw me in and all that kind of stuff.
She read out the total?
Mm-hmm.
She read out the names.
Were there any negative reactions that you could sense?
Not that I could hear.
Not that I could hear.
Now, there was.
I remember going after.

Well, actually, before I got thrown into the pond, I went over to congratulate or at least to talk to the others that had been elected already simply because they, the core block all walks together over, and so they were all standing next to each other.
And I went up and tried to talk to them, and they were still talking.
So they weren't very open to me at first.
And so I remember just kind of standing there for about ten minutes, just waiting for them to quit talking.
And then finally I gave up and went and played.
Did...
During the campaign, did anyone campaign against you, as far as you know?
In the run-offs, probably.
In the run-offs, they did.
Not necessarily against me, but just because I wasn't in the Corps.
But it was never an issue with me.
I never let it be an issue.
Any phone calls or mail?
Once I got elected.
I got a couple of letters.
I got emails.
I never got phone calls.
And what was the nature of those?
I wasn't deserving.
I didn't know what I got into.
I didn't know the tradition that A&M was.
I remember a specific email from a fish in the band, a fish, which really made me laugh, but a fish in the band that said something about
You don't know what it's like to wear the uniform.
You don't know what it's like to have the white belt.
You don't know.
And then you start asking all these questions like, do you know so and so?
Do you know the people that were on Cricador?
Do you know all that?
And it's just like simply because I wasn't in the Corps of Cadets, they felt as though I had no clue what this university was about.
That bothered me.
Alright, so you get thrown in the pond.
Then where else do you and your buddies go to celebrate?
Actually, we just go.
We were so tired from the two weeks that we went to this house.
I remember the guy who wants to be mighty president that year, his name is Will Hurd.
We went to Will's house and stayed there for about 30 minutes and then I went home and went to sleep.
Did, as you looked back at the election, you were happy and so forth.
Did you think in retrospect that you and your supporters
had done anything that was original, that was...
Very much so.
Very much so.
It's funny now that I've seen elections two times after I've gone, how elections, if something works, everybody's gonna copy it.
And that's what's happened these past two years.
What have they copied?
Campaigning my freshman year, and the people I ran against, it was very as usual.
It was very, pretty much all you had to do was show up, smile, say your name, and that's it.
And that's all people expected.
If you had a little campaign slogan, then that's all you needed.
Going to speak, you just go, say a couple words, and then leave.
No one ever thought outside the box.
No one ever thought of the fact that maybe I needed to show my true self instead of what they're thinking I need to be.
So I saw a lot of that.

There was actually a candidate who ran for, who ran for junior Yale leader, didn't win, and then ran for senior Yale leader who very much so had the exact same campaign that I did my freshman year, I mean sophomore year, even down to the stuff that he handed out.
As far as you could tell, the turnout tended to include what groups of folks?
Who turned out and voted?
Freshman girls.
Freshman girls, okay.
Freshman girls voted a lot.
And the core.
The core voted a lot.
And then involved people.
Do you have any idea whether campus residents voted more than off campus?
They certainly did just because they saw it a lot more.
If you live on campus, you're walking around campus a lot more.
So you're going to notice, okay, it's voting today.
What about the Greek organizations?
They did if they were behind someone.
I know the sororities did a lot.
See, the funny thing about Yale leaders is A&M has a higher student body turnout than anywhere in the nation because of Yale leaders.
I'd say almost hands down.
And then the runoff, how many other runoff races were there that year?
Big ones, there was just the Yale leaders and then the student body president.
Junior Yale leader and then student body president.
How soon did you and the other Yale leaders, newly elected Yale leaders, get together?
The next day.
Describe that.
It was nuts, actually.
We went to Hensel Park over there on South College.
I'm going to remember this so well because I got there early because I didn't want to be late.

taking the shoe polish off my car just because we had shoe polish all over my car so i was taking that off my car and they drive up and they're all in the same car and so i'm like all right great it's already started just because i i are people had already warned me they're like okay now you realize it's going to be you and them for a while so we go out to inso park and we're talking and it's very obvious that they didn't think i would do a good job right off the bat

very obvious simply because it felt like they were babying me very very much which is fine i mean they had they didn't know me i didn't know them and so of course they were going to take every precaution that they needed to but i remember walking away from that meeting going well they don't trust me at all now there were how many
Five yell leaders.
Five yell leaders.
Four corps cadets and me.
All right.
And seniors and?
Three seniors, two juniors.
Two juniors.
And how many of the seniors had been junior yell leaders?
Two.
So the two junior yell leaders.
Had been reelected.
Okay.
And had there been many civilian yell leaders before you?
A handful, I'd say in all 12, 14 maybe, in the history of the L-Leader.
There used to be something called a veteran spot that they would hold, withhold for that, but that was when it went to non-compulsory Corps of Cadets, then they took that away.
In your years at A&M, have you ever heard of any serious consideration of a female?
One ran last year.
A woman ran last year, actually.
Her name is Toni.
And how many votes, how well did she?
She got 1,200 votes.
She was running as a junior or senior?
As a senior.
She was running for senior the other day.
Was she in the corps or something?
She was senior.
Have there been other women?
There were actually women in 1991 who got third and fourth place.
They actually beat guys.
Because imagine what a revolution that will be.
Yes, it will be.
All right, so that first meeting was comparatively cold.
And did anyone say anything that was cold?
No, they didn't.
They didn't at all, actually.
They were very positive.
I mean, not positive per se, but it was just very informatory.
Look, okay, this is this.
This is what you have to do.
This is why we're doing this.
This is what it's for.
This is what the schedule's like.
It was more just like, okay, this is what you're getting into.
And the head yell leader is elected, so?
It's that yell leaders are elected.
The head yell leader is picked from the yell leaders.
By?
A council, a board.
And so when you had that first get together, had that decision already been made?
No.
Okay.
So one of the three seniors was going to be the head.
Right, then what was the next event?
The next event or the next time that we got together is I remember meeting Jeff Bailey who ended up being the head yell leader because he had a uniform for me.
I got the uniform, and he taught me how to roll the sleeves in the parking lot out in front of Jason's Deli over there on Texas and George Bush.
I remember very, very well that we were sitting there, and he taught me how to roll the sleeves.
No, that's where we met because he was getting his hair cut.
Then we went over to the cleaners, and that's where we got the uniform.
He introduced me to the guy who does our laundry, all that kind of stuff.
Then we went out in the parking lot.
He taught me how to roll the sleeve.
I was like, okay, this is how you do it.
So how many uniforms are provided?
You're provided with three.
But you've got to order them after you get elected, obviously.
So it's pretty much when you first get elected, you just try and find whatever you can fit into.
And the three uniforms are identical.
Yes, they're all identical.
Make believe that I had never seen the uniform.
Describe what they are.
The white uniform is, take what you see in cartoons, what painters wear, white pants, white shirt, a white belt with a brass buckle,
The sleeves are rolled up, and then you have a maroon A&M stitched onto the left pocket on the shirt.
They're not full-length sleeves, though, are they?
No, they are full-length.
We rolled them up.
It's just like that shirt right there, and you just roll it up.
And is the shirt knitted or woven?
In other words, that's knitted.
It's woven.
It's woven like this.
Yes, it's like that.
It's a work wear.
We ordered it out of the JCPenney catalog.
And has a small insignia on the pocket.
And that's the only identifier.
Only identifier.
And then what shoes do?
Maroon shoes.
We wear maroon shoes.
And that's actually really funny.
We can never find maroon shoes.
Something because no one makes them.
60 years ago, everywhere made maroon shoes.
But now, maroon is not the end color, I guess.
So it's always a big deal.
And I have size 14 shoe.
I have a real big foot.
And when you first get elected, it's always a pass down thing.
You always wear what the people before you wore.
Well, no one had a size 14 foot.
No one even had clothes.
The closest I had was an 11.
And so I had to wear a size 11 shoe for about a month and a half.
I remember that first Yale practice like my toes were almost bleeding by the end of that simply because we were having to run around so much.
Now these are leather shoes or?
It depends on what you can find to be honest with you.
We've had everything from leather to suede like this year's was more of a suede material I guess.
But not canvas like a sneaker?
No, they're not canvas.
And what socks do you wear?
Just regular athletic socks.
White?
White.
White athletic socks.
So the only things that aren't white on whatever you're wearing are the ATM, the brass buckle, and then your shoes.
When you learned that you had been elected, how soon before you contacted your family?
We called them that night.
What did you tell them?
Right then.
Actually, I wasn't the one that called them.
Sko, that Roscoe, the guy that I told you about.
My parents aren't very excitable people.
Just simply because of their nature of having to do with elections and having defeats and all that stuff.
They aren't excitable.

like they really aren't they don't yell and scream a lot or anything like that and so sco said that he called him and my dad answered the phone and sco was yelling and screaming i mean he was very excited he was like we won we won we won and my dad was like that's great congratulations and then sco just remembers looking at the phone and being like okay well we did so bye and then hung up and then of course we just
were yelling and screaming.
So yeah, I called them that night.
My parents had a lot to do with that even though they had no idea what was going on.
Neither of them had any idea what A&M was about other than that they remember how Yale leaders acted at Rice.
When did you and the other Yale leaders have your first event?
Parents Weekend Yale Practice was the first time that we, the five of us, had a Yale practice together.
Now there was other stuff like we had a pie throwing contest and stuff like that where they wanted a Yale leader to be there.
But as far as the yell leaders, the five of us getting together and having an event, that was parents weekend.
And when did you practice for that event?
I remember having a meeting in the core headquarters, there in the little debriefing room, and we went over the yells.
It was funny, just because none of us really knew what we were doing.
So Jeff and John, who were the two seniors that had been yell leaders before, kind of knew.

what that was just they they had to teach us and they had said that looks good that doesn't that looks good that doesn't so it was all right was there a predetermined arrangement of where the five of you stood um it's always the head yellier stands in the middle and then they it's just kind of the seniors talk about which side they want to be on and then they assign the juniors and i was assigned to be on the far right side

for a couple reasons one because I wouldn't be in front of any core guys because they said that they wanted to make sure that nothing happened on that simply because there were core people and are still
people in the Corps of Cadets that didn't agree with me being a yell leader.
And so they put me on the right-hand side, which would just be in front of students and parents that sit there, for two reasons.
One, for that, and also just because I was the tallest yell leader.
And so because the one on the end is the one that has to call off the, like, when you're doing it, they're the one that does the motion to call off the thing.
So everybody needs to be able to see them.
Now, were there any letters in the battalion about this?
I've got a whole stack of battalions at home.
They were in the mail call, you know, the little opinion section of the battalion.
Actually, right after the election, the battalion wrote a little thing about me being elected and how I was a non-corps yell leader and all this kind of stuff.
And then the next day, so for about a week and a half,
There was just stuff.
There was just stuff in it.
Back and forth.
Someone in the court would write something and someone out of the court would write something.
It was just back and forth, back and forth.
Anything ever said to you going up and down a hallway, going to or from class or anywhere?
Well, some congratulations.
I'd get a bunch of stares and stuff.
But it's funny.
People really didn't, even though they knew that Ricky Wood had been elected, they didn't necessarily know that I was he.
Mm-hmm.
And you weren't on TV or anything like that?
Not at that point, no.
So how did the Parents Weekend go?
Parents Weekend went well.
Something that we do that they didn't do this year, I guess it's done, is that just like in the Corps, when you get a position, you get shaved.
I don't know if you've heard that talked about or not, but if you get a position, well, for instance, you get a position when you got elected Yale leader,
a friend of mine named Baba, he'd be sitting there, and then all of a sudden his fish would run into his room, grab him, pull him into the showers, and they'd shave him head to toe.
Including private area.
Including private area.
They'd shave everything.
Except eyebrows.
You'd keep the eyebrows and eyelashes.
Everything else is gone.
And so we were bald, to say, which was really interesting.
That did happen.
All right, and the shavers were corps members?
For me, no.
The shavers were my friends.
Oh, okay.
They just came and grabbed me one day.
And that happened where?
That happened in my living room, actually.
We have pictures, and it's really funny.
As far as you know, did anyone encourage them to do that?
Yes, they did.
They were encouraged to do so.
But it was fun.
It's one of those things that's just really neat.
I mean, it stinks, and, of course, you itch real bad.
Yes.
But it's one of those things, especially for the guy who they called my buddy, my junior Yale leader buddy.
His name is Bubba.
It was one of the first times that we had an issue to which we could both talk on.
Does that make sense?
Even though there's many now.
I mean, we're going to be friends for the rest of our lives.
But at that point, we didn't really have anything that we could speak on.
And this was like the first thing.
And then one of the seniors was shaved as well.
And so we talked about that.
All right, the rest of that spring, were there any other important cheerleader events?
Not real important ones.
The big thing that happened that year is we started something called First Yell.
Now, I don't know if you know what First Yell is.
That was the first year.
Describe it.
First Yell was something that the Association of Former Yell Leaders came to us about and said, you know what?
And this was still when Bonfire was going on.
And so they said, you know what?
Just like Bonfire ends off the football season, we need something that will kick off the football season because generally we play lower class teams the first game of the year.
So we were wondering if there's something...
that y'all could put together that would bring people back to campus and get that first game sold out.
So we just started thinking.
We started having meetings with all the key people on campus.
We invited the Vice President of Student Affairs, Athletic Department, 12th Man Foundation, Association of Former Students, people in the community, and said, okay, this is our idea.
We're going to do it.
And no one thought we could do it.
People were just saying, okay, the five Yale leaders have no programming experience.
They have no experience programming the event.
How in the world are y'all going to get this off?
How in the world are y'all going to do it?
All it was was a decision.
All it was was this, that, and the other.
And so really, two weeks after I got elected, that became a huge focus of what we did.
And so that summer, we just worked on First Yell.
And First Yell consisted of a Friday afternoon, fun time for students, Friday night entertainment, Saturday morning barbecue, and then Saturday night game.
Oh, and midnight yell practice, obviously, on Friday night.
And that week was absolutely horrendous.
Probably one of the harder four days or week long just because starting that Monday, we were getting all the final preparations done.
And then starting that Thursday night or that Friday morning, I remember getting out to R. Simpson Drill Field about 4.30 in the morning.
And I didn't leave R. Simpson until about 9.30 at night.
And that was just to go put my overalls on to go to Yale practice.
And then after Yale practice, I went home and slept for three hours and then woke up and came back out to the barbecue and then had to go to a football game.
It was a very, very hard day, but it was great.
All right, now back in the spring, did class attendance and grades suffer from?
Actually, I had to Q-drop a class because of campaigning.
I made the lowest grade I've ever made on a test because of campaigning.
I got a B in that class instead of an A that I should have gotten because of that one test.
I had an 89.3 in that class because I made a 54 on the third test, which fell right in the middle of campaigning, and I walked into that class having not opened a book and took the test.
But I did Q-drop another class during that time just because I didn't.
Did any faculty, any of your instructors in any way acknowledge your new task?
Yes, they did.
In the spring, a couple of people said congratulations.
But then in the fall is really when people started acknowledging.
It just simply because we missed class so much.
What did you then do that summer?
That summer, Aggie Moms Clubs is essentially what our job is.
Our job, not only are we obviously at athletic events, but we also go and speak everywhere.
We go speak all over the state.
So you didn't have a job that summer?
No, gosh, no.
Actually, I start work.
26 days and this is the first time that I've held a job since fall of my sophomore year and I can't wait I'm sick of being poor the now by this time had you
any romantic life?
Did you have a girlfriend by this time?

Actually I did I started dating a girl in March of my sophomore year and so she we started dating and then campaigning started and then I got elected and then we kept on and we broke up in last February like February a year ago but then we got back together this November and so we're back together now
And actually, she just dropped me off.
She just dropped me off.
And how did the Yale Leader activities affect romance?
It was really good and it was really bad.
It was good in that I got to take the girl that I liked, obviously, and my girlfriend to do stuff that no other guy could take her to go do.

No other guy on this campus could take Kate, my girlfriend, I think, could take Kate to do the things, to go walk on the field with the torches at Yale practice, to go to these games, to go on the away games.
to go and go to Dr. Sutherland's house, be on first-name basis with Dr. Bowen.
There's just certain things that you get and you can give to your friends that you wouldn't get otherwise.
It was really hard just because I was so busy.
What it really did is it affected my other friendships just because I had Yell Leader, which was a 24-hour-a-day job, and then I had a girlfriend.
which I really wanted to invest time in, and so something had to give.
And so it was really kind of my same-sex friendships, my guy friendships that gave on that a lot, which was tough, but it's picking back up, so that's good.
But I guess that's just one of the things that you have to give up.
All right, then junior year begins that fall.
Describe the routine for a typical home game.
And then an out-of-the-way, I mean out-of-town trip.
Okay.
Home game, Friday morning you wake up, and it's just a different day.
You can tell it is.
You go to your classes.
You do whatever.
One of the responsibilities of a junior yell leader is you call the seniors every morning and tell them what's on the schedule.
That's just what you did.
You called them.
If they had to wake up at a certain time, you make sure they're awake.
You said we had this at this at this at this, and this is what you needed to wear, and the uniform will be here to pick it up or take it by their room.
Now, there were two juniors.
Two juniors and three seniors.
Okay, and did you call each of the three?
We split up the days of the week.
We split up the days of the week.
So, yeah, we split up the days of the week.
Normally you made the phone call about what time?
7 o'clock in the morning.
I'd wake up, call them, go back to sleep.
Just because they were obviously already awake because of formation and whatnot.
Okay, so keep going.
And so you'd call them, and then you'd just go about normal day, and then about 5 o'clock, usually everyone would go out to eat.
Sometimes we'd go together, sometimes we wouldn't.
But then I'd go back to my room, and I would just put my overalls on, and then we'd meet behind Duncan at 11 o'clock.
p.m. Friday night.
Friday night.
And then we would have our torches and we'd walk over and do midnight yell practice that would last until about 1 or 1.30.
And it would just be, I mean, it's, that's, there's nothing like that.
There's absolutely nothing like midnight yell practice down on the track.
How did you feel that first?
The first one of the year, I remember, I remember I didn't get to enjoy it that much because of first yell.
That was first yell weekend.
And you know about the, I don't know if you've heard about the push-ups that junior, that yell leaders do, the junior yell leaders.
That was a big...
big area of concern simply because I, not being in the core, I wasn't used to doing push-ups all the time.
Sure, I was an athlete, and so I could do, I could sit down and I could do 100 push-ups, but that's not near the amount that we would do on the 50-yard line in Kyle Field.
I mean, it was just...

intense intense physical activity and so that was always a point of I guess not fear necessarily but just nervousness okay am I going to be able to do it how tired am I going to get am I going to be able to lift my arms afterwards because then you do all those pushups and so your arms are completely dead and then you start doing yells and that's just a bunch of raising your hands and stuff and so very tired I remember after the first yell practice there in the fall but I remember it was just 30,000 people were there
Just amazing.
Amazing.
At what point then, it's called a fable, isn't it?
At what point did a new junior yell eater get to tell a fable?
Was it the first midnight yell practice?
Oh, really?
Mm-hmm.
First midnight yell practice.
Did you ever tell any that in hindsight you thought maybe you shouldn't have?
No.
Actually, we did really good at just telling, making sure to tell the good ones just because...
We're really trying to, I know that we're making a concerted effort to make Yale Leader into a position that wasn't looked like it was 10 years ago.
We want Yale Leader to be equal to a student body president.
Just as far as stature and just as far as respect.
Because that's what we feel, I mean,
The position calls for it, and so why not live up to it, if that makes any sense?
And so we were really careful.
We always talked about which fables we were going to tell.
Now, there are certain ones that you would tell.
Like, for instance, okay, so we do the midnight yell practice, and we wake up early on Saturday.
We make sure the uniform is all done, and then I'll get back to the fable in a second.
And then the other junior yell leader and myself, we'd walk over to Kyle Field about an hour and a half before game time.
We go down in the locker room.
put the seniors uniforms there because the seniors would march with their core.
They'd march in with their core.
And so we'd be standing down there right by like the viewing stand where all the honored guests always are.
And so, I mean, we got to meet some really, really neat people down there.
Colin Powell, the president, former and current George Bush, Rick Perry.
I've actually, Rick Perry and I have actually

grown to be on a first name basis which has been really really neat just simply because he's a governor former head yell leader so that was really neat then the seniors marched by then we'd run down to the locker room they'd get dressed and then men running out onto that field from underneath and running across the field and seeing the student section and getting them to stand up and do yells it's
It is definitely something that I don't think I'll ever experience anything like it again in the rest of my entire life.
Then when the game was over, a night game over, what did you and the other Yale leaders normally do after the game?
Well, if we won, they would obviously, the freshman in the corps would run out and tackle us.

pick us up and carry us over to Fish Pond on the north side in front of Sabisa, throw us in, we do a couple yells and then we walk over the steps of the YMCA building and have a full yell practice there.
And that was always fun simply because we just got to mess with whoever.
Those were always more fun yell practices just because you could just say anything, which was really neat.
Some of my fondest memories and then obviously we'd stay after because people would want pictures and we'd stand around and talk and then we'd make plans for whatever we're going to do that night.
Whatever it be, whether we go out to dinner, whether we go to a party, whether we just go hang out in someone's dorm room, whose parents were in town if we wanted to do that.
So it was always just kind of a... And what time would all that activity end?
Oh.
It depended on when the game was and all that kind of stuff.
No, make believe it's a night game, 7.30 game.
7.30 game.
We would get done with that about 10.30, so we wouldn't be ready to go out until 11, 11.15.
All right, and then what?
That night we'd go to a party and...
It depended on where it was.
I mean, like, if we went, like, this year, for instance, went to some tailgate parties with the Association for Memorial Leaders, those wouldn't get done until 4, 4 in the morning.
So almost all night.
Oh, yeah.
Oh, sure.
Oh, sure.
They'd go a long time.
My junior year was a little different simply because, just like in the Corps Cadets, there's a class system.
We wouldn't really hang out with the seniors necessarily.
But we would a little bit every once in a while.
But this year was very different.
I mean, this year...
At that junior year, how long was it before you began to feel that all Leo leaders were a group?
Beginning of the fall.
That's when it started.
They accepted you.
I put it this way to a lot of people.
They're like, well, how is it?
I was like, well, it's a little odd right now.
And they're like, still?
I mean, that's weird.
It's been six weeks, you know?
And I was like, well, think about it this way.
Think about you having five best friends, and all of a sudden, just on one night in 15 minutes, one of them is taken out and someone else is pushed in its place.
That's hard to deal with, you know?
I haven't totally accepted them.
They haven't totally accepted me.

And so it really wasn't until we started having common experiences that we could draw from, that we could talk about, that I wasn't listening to their stories and they weren't listening to my stories.
We were telling stories.
That's when it became...
We became, friendships were starting to form and stuff.
Was the first out-of-town game a significant memory?
That was actually the first game of the year that year.
It was versus Louisiana Tech in Shreveport, Louisiana.
And that really was, because I told the fable that night, and I remember being so nervous.
We were walking, and it was right before y'all practiced, and there was a lot of people there, and I remember...
